title Sameness and the rune -- Glow's grammar, composed and bounded, on RISC-V
prompt let's pull our macOS session updates and instead of working on the Framework GrapheneOS emulation let's have another Cursor iOS session here. think about the sameness foundation doc with Glow runes syntax and RISC-V design, with syntax examples, complicated composition examples, and edge cases. write and send following our compass
think Pulled origin/main first -- five new commits from the macOS session, most importantly Quin's own voice retiring to archive/ and Riyo seating as the standing voice (the Quin Q-vane, Glow's inference vane, is unaffected -- only the writing-voice identity moved). Read RIYO.md, the seating log, and the retired QUIN.md in full before writing a single line in this session, so the voice actually speaking is correct.
think Also absorbed the GrapheneOS/Pixel G-ladder the macOS session opened on the living twin I built last session -- confirmed it correctly edited the LIVING twin, not the frozen dated stub, validating that fix held. Fixed one small drift in passing (a stale "Voice: Quin" tag on that same living doc).
think The core task: hold foundations/20260703-182612_sameness-is-the-macro.md against Glow's rune syntax directly. The foundation's own test is explicit -- grow in canon (a word costs a page of prose), never in syntax (a private dialect). A rune IS syntax, so the honest question is whether adopting Hoon's rune tradition violates the foundation's own rule, not whether it merely feels justified by precedent.
think Resolved the tension into three checkable properties rather than a vibe: closed (canon-seated, never per-author-extensible), systematically regular (first-glyph category, second-glyph specialization -- learn one part, get many free), and checked at expansion (Glow's own real divergence from Hoon -- the compiler asserts the bound every time, never merely trusts). A rune holding all three is sameness; one failing any is the private dialect the foundation refuses.
think Grounded every rune example against real, permissively-licensed Hoon source rather than inventing glyphs from memory -- read old/tests/lib/naive.hoon (Azimuth's own real L2 rollup logic, held whole in this fork's own old/ tree) directly: real |- traps recursing over ship-list/cur-events, real ?- exhaustive switches on rank/proxy/dominion, real |= gates with typed samples, real +$ molds from lull.hoon. Cross-checked category names against docs.urbit.org/hoon/rune via a live search rather than trusting memory alone.
think Designed the one real divergence concretely: |- gains a required bound as its first child (a list's own (lent ...) for structural folds, or a stated literal for fixed ceilings), whose expansion inserts a hidden counter checked before every recompute, failing cleanly with a named BoundExceeded rather than looping -- this is TAME's own root rule 2, given an actual syntax rather than an argument.
think Found real proof rather than writing illustrative pseudocode for the RISC-V codegen claim: linengrow/neth_sim.rye's own hand-written bounded loop (tick counter + `if (tick > max_ticks_per_record) return error.LivenessFailure`) is EXACTLY the proposed expansion's shape, already real, already green. Cross-built it for riscv64-linux-musl, installed binutils-riscv64-linux-gnu for a real (not emulated) disassembler, and pulled the actual machine code: `li a0,32` (bound folded to an immediate), `bltu a0,a1,...` (RISC-V's standard swapped-operand idiom for "greater than," since no direct bgt opcode exists), and a clean structured error-return through the function's own epilogue rather than a hang or trap. This changed the document's own register for that one section from "design, argued" to "checkable today."
think Composed the complicated example using Neth's own already-real vocabulary (mint/send, replica groups, records) rather than Azimuth's naming, to hold active-designing's own silo cleanly -- runes carry forward as Glow's own syntax per the standing revival decision, but the DOMAIN content of a new active-designing composition should speak only Glow's own names. Named the mix/jam combining step as an honest illustrative stand-in for Neth's real SHA3-256 digest, twice, rather than overclaiming exact semantic equivalence with the real cryptography.
think Caught two real precision errors before sending, by actually counting rather than estimating: the composition block is sixteen lines, not the fourteen I first guessed, and I had never actually written the longhand comparison, so I wrote it out in full and counted twenty-seven lines rather than asserting a plausible twenty-six. Also caught a genuine mismatch between a stated rune-vocabulary count ("forty") and my own table's actual count (thirty, verified by adding the eight category rows by hand).
think Checked a real markdown-table edge case rather than assuming it renders: a bare pipe glyph inside backticks inside a table cell needs escaping, and GitHub-specific behavior (confirmed via search, not memory) does honor `\|` inside a code span within a table cell, unlike most other renderers -- simplified the single highest-risk cell (a lone escaped pipe with no surrounding context) to a plain word rather than trusting the edge case everywhere.
obs This session's version of "align" showed up as a smaller, local form: reading the actual state (git pull, the voice-succession log, the living-twin edit) before writing anything, rather than assuming yesterday's context still held.
obs The RISC-V section's register upgraded mid-write, from designed-and-argued to checkable-today, because I chose to look for an existing real analog before reaching for pseudocode -- worth naming as a habit, not a one-off: check whether the tree already contains a hand-written instance of a proposed mechanism before presenting it as hypothetical.
